Doc Spatz:<br><br>
To quote you from site 20, I believe:<br><br>
&gt;&quot;I am the voice in your ear that says that you were wrong, that you should not have gone, that you should not have killed, that you suck.&quot;&lt;<br><br>
Now you say:<br><br>
&gt;&quot;Do we need to keep attacking each other, or get on with understanding each other. Hey Alex, Tom Dier, Art V., I'm talking to you!&quot;&lt;<br><br>
I am now faced with an incongruity. On the one hand, I feel a definite problem in arriving at an understanding of what appears to be a unilateral view, yours, and no one else's. On the other hand, you assertion of addressing me in the context of understanding, in light of your words on post 20 is a contradiction. Who is attacking and who is understanding? Is the voice in my ear you talking to me?<br><br>
Since you have not yet replied to my recent questions on post 6, the credibility gap of requested clarifications grows to your disadvantage. If you really want a meeting of the minds, then clearly my requests for clarification are to be expected in light of these perceived incongruities in your philosophy toward Vietnam Veterans.<br><br>
Again, as I said on post 6, thanks for your concern.<br><br>
I hope I have fulfilled your wish of:<br><br>
&gt;&quot;I ask for honest thought, not quick anger and unthinking<br>
responses.&quot;&lt; <br><br>
